  "prompt": "In a group of 50 people, what are the odds of 2 having the same birthday?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step using the \"Birthday Problem\" calculation:\n\n1) First, calculate the probability that NO two people share a birthday\n\u2022 Assume 365 possible birthdays (ignoring leap years)\n\u2022 First person can have any birthday: 365/365\n\u2022 Second person must have a different birthday: 364/365\n\u2022 Third person must have a different birthday from first two: 363/365\n\u2022 Continue for all 50 people\n\n2) The mathematical formula is:\nP(no shared birthday) = 365! / (365^50 * (365-50)!)\n\n3) Calculating this gives approximately 0.0297 (2.97%)\n\n4) Therefore, the probability of at least two people sharing a birthday is:\n1 - 0.0297 = 0.9703 or about 97.03%\n\n5) So in a group of 50 people, there's a 97.03% chance that at least two people share a birthday.\n\nInterestingly, you only need 23 people to have a 50% chance of a shared birthday, which surprises many people.",
